      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Pool Safety Certificates When Selling Queensland Property: What Sellers Must Do
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        If your property has a pool, Queensland law imposes specific obligations before you can complete a sale. Understanding the two compliance paths available to you, and what happens if your pool fails inspection, will save you from last-minute delays.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Pool safety compliance is one of the pre-sale obligations that sellers most commonly leave too late. It surfaces in conversation as a checkbox item, something to sort out before settlement, when in practice it needs to be in place well before your listing goes to contract. A pool safety certificate cannot be rushed if your fencing or barriers need work, and passing the obligation to the buyer through a Form 36 notice carries its own consequences that are often poorly understood. This article covers both paths and what to expect from the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal requirement</h2>
      <p>Under the Building Act 1975 (Qld) and the Building Regulation 2021, a property with a swimming pool or spa pool cannot be sold without either a current pool safety certificate being provided to the buyer before the contract is signed, or a Form 36 Notice of No Pool Safety Certificate being given to the buyer, which transfers the obligation to obtain the certificate to them after settlement. Both paths satisfy the legislative requirement, but they have different practical consequences that matter when you are in the middle of a sale campaign.</p>

      <p>Pool safety certificates must be issued by a licensed pool safety inspector. This is a specific licence separate from a building inspector's licence. You can check whether an inspector is licensed through the Queensland Building and Construction Commission register. Do not rely on a building and pest inspector or a general contractor to tell you whether your pool fencing complies. The licence exists because pool barrier compliance requires specialised knowledge of the Queensland code.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the inspection actually covers</h2>
      <p>A pool safety inspection is a check of the physical barriers separating the pool from the rest of the property and from neighbouring properties. The inspector assesses the fence height and construction, gate mechanisms including self-closing and self-latching function, non-climbable zones (the 900mm zone on the outside of the fence from which a child cannot climb to reach the latch), gaps under and between fence panels, and the condition of any windows or doors that open directly to the pool area and must have appropriate latching.</p>

      <p>Common failure items in Brisbane homes include gate hinges and latches that have corroded or sagged over time, gaps under timber fencing that has moved with the season, non-compliant non-climbable zones created by garden furniture, storage, or pool equipment placed on the outside of the fence, and older pool fences that meet a superseded standard but not the current code. If your pool area has been modified, landscaped, or had structures added since the fence was originally installed, there is a reasonable chance the non-climbable zone has been compromised without anyone realising it.</p>

      <p>A pool safety certificate, once issued, is valid for two years for a private pool and one year for a shared pool. If your certificate has expired, you need a fresh inspection before selling. An in-date certificate that has been issued to you as the owner can be used in a sale, as it transfers with the property. An in-date certificate issued to a previous owner also transfers, provided it remains valid at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The two compliance paths: Form 23 versus Form 36</h2>
      <p>Path one is to obtain the pool safety certificate (Form 23) before the contract is signed and provide it to the buyer as part of the disclosure documents. This is the approach most sellers take and the one that typically produces a smoother sale. A buyer who sees a current certificate knows what they are getting. They do not need to factor in unknown compliance costs, and they cannot use pool safety as a negotiation point once the contract is signed.</p>

      <p>Path two is to issue the buyer with a Form 36 Notice of No Pool Safety Certificate. This formally acknowledges that no certificate exists and gives the buyer 90 days after settlement to obtain one themselves. The buyer becomes responsible for the inspection costs and for any rectification work required. This sounds appealing to sellers who know their pool fencing needs work, but in practice it creates a buyer objection before the contract is even signed. Buyers (and their agents and building inspectors) treat a Form 36 as a signal that compliance costs are unknown and potentially significant. That uncertainty gets priced into their offer. Sellers who take the Form 36 path to avoid spending $300 to $800 on an inspection and minor rectification work often find themselves negotiating against an imaginary deficiency that is larger than the real one.</p>

      <p>The exception where a Form 36 makes genuine sense is where the pool fencing has a known major non-compliance that would require substantial structural work, or where the property is a development site where the pool will be demolished or significantly altered. In those cases, the transparency of the Form 36 is appropriate and the buyer understands the situation. For most residential sales, obtaining the certificate is the better path.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the pool fails the inspection</h2>
      <p>If a licensed inspector finds non-compliances, they will provide a written deficiency notice identifying what needs to be rectified and what standard each item must meet. You have three options: engage a licensed contractor to do the work and then arrange a re-inspection, negotiate with the buyer around the deficiency if you have already signed a Form 36, or if you have not yet gone to contract, address the deficiencies before listing.</p>

      <p>The re-inspection process is straightforward for minor items. Gate mechanisms, latches, and small gap repairs can usually be done by a qualified tradesperson within a few days, and a re-inspection can be booked quickly. Larger structural issues with the fence line itself take longer. If your fence needs to be partially rebuilt or relocated, allow four to eight weeks minimum, depending on trades availability and council requirements for the specific work.</p>

      <p>Sellers who discover a non-compliance mid-campaign and have not yet signed a contract are in the better position, they can address the work, get the certificate, and proceed without the issue affecting their negotiation. Sellers who discover a problem after contract is signed under a Form 36 arrangement may find themselves in a more difficult position if the buyer uses the certificate cost as leverage during the settlement period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How timing affects your campaign</h2>
      <p>The pool safety certificate should be arranged before your listing goes live, not in the week before settlement. The reason is straightforward: buyers and their building inspectors look at pool fencing during open homes and pre-purchase inspections. If they can see obvious non-compliances, the absence of a certificate will come up. Your agent also needs to know the certificate status before any offer is received, because it affects the documentation attached to the contract.</p>

      <p>Book your inspection as early as possible, at least three to four weeks before your intended listing date. This gives you time to address any deficiencies and arrange a re-inspection before you go to market. Most inspectors in Brisbane can schedule an appointment within a week or two, but rectification work and re-inspection add time. Do not compress this into the final fortnight before your listing goes live.</p>

      <p>Inspection costs for a standard residential pool in Brisbane currently sit in the range of $150 to $300, depending on the inspector and the complexity of the fence layout. Re-inspection fees are typically $100 to $200. Rectification work varies from a few hundred dollars for gate hardware through to several thousand for structural fence repairs, but the majority of non-compliances identified in Brisbane homes are minor and inexpensive to address.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Body corporate pools and apartments</h2>
      <p>If you are selling an apartment or townhouse where the pool is a shared facility managed by the body corporate, the pool safety certificate obligation sits with the body corporate, not with the individual lot owner. Your solicitor will confirm this as part of the contract preparation. As a seller, you need to ensure the body corporate has a current certificate for the shared pool and that it is attached to or referenced in your sale documentation. If the body corporate does not have a current certificate, it is their obligation to obtain one, not yours. Your solicitor can advise on how this is managed in practice for your specific property.</p>

      <p>The broader body corporate disclosure regime for apartments and townhouses is handled separately through the community management statement and body corporate records search, which your solicitor manages as part of the contract. Pool safety for shared facilities is one component of that broader disclosure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical summary</h2>
      <p>If your property has a pool, arrange the safety inspection at least three to four weeks before listing. Get the certificate if your fencing is compliant or close to compliant. Address deficiencies early, before they become a buyer issue. Only use the Form 36 path if there is a genuine reason the certificate cannot be obtained before the sale, and go into that conversation with your eyes open about how buyers respond to unknown compliance costs. Tell your agent what the certificate status is before any buyer enquiries are received, so they can answer questions accurately and attach the right documentation when the contract is prepared.</p>

